            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>Understood by Guarducci (ed.pr.) to be a verse epigram for a doctor, likely of the second century CE, of a type familiar in mainland Italy, and perhaps to be associated with a sanctuary of Aesclepias in the vicinity (a statue of Hygeia was found in the area also). Manganaro instead suggested an interpretation relating to the construction of a thermal spa / bath building, perhaps in the fourth century (strongly rejected by Robert). <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000632">ISic000632</ref> was found in close proximity.</p>
            </div>
